{
  "texts": [
    "Traditional pollsters are subject to specific diagnostics which evaluate the degree to which they made sensible decisions, and were responsible in their reporting during election campaigns.",
    "Classic examples of these post-mortem evaluations are the report on the UK polling industry after the major upset in the 2015 election (Sturgis et al. 2016), as well as a similar report following the 2016 US election (Kennedy et al. 2018).",
    "Moreover, rankings of pollsters are generally possible based on clear choices of research design which are made by each firm, as well as their measurable accuracy from election to election.",
    "These inquiries into polling performance in turn can affect the reputation of pollsters, and lead to higher or lower credibility.",
    "If evidence of explicit manipulation were to come to light, the polling firm in question could suffer a potentially fatal blow."
  ]
}